If you're writing a macro plugin, there are a couple different places you have to deal with parameter types: you specify the types in your plugin descriptor (which I think ends up accessible from {{MacroFormDetails.getMetadata()}}, so the Macro Browser knows what to do with them), and in your {{Macro.execute()}} implementation you cast the params to the appropriate types.

There's some room for inconsistency there, though.  It would be nice if {{execute()}} gave you a slightly richer parameters object, that you could do something like:

{code}int foo = params.get("foo", MacroParameterType.INT, Integer.class);{code}

or maybe:

{code}int foo = params.getInt("foo");{code}

either of which would give you a param of the correct type, validated against the declared type in the metadata.  Alternatively, there could be an extra helper method on {{MacroModuleDescriptor}} that you could do the same kind of thing with:

{code}int foo = descriptor.getIntParameter(params, "foo");{code}

